<DOC><DOCNO> AP891113-0215 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0736EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     11-13 0812</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0850</SECOND><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Teamsters local president who has beenendorsed for the national union's presidency said further reformsin the Teamsters will help rank-and-file members combat the union'sreputation as a corrupt organization. Ron Carey, president of the7,000-member Teamsters Local 804 in New York City, is the firstmember to say he will take advantage of new election procedures andchallenge the union's leadership.   He was endorsed Sunday by the Teamsters for a Democratic Union,a dissident group within the 1.6 million-member InternationalBrotherhood of Teamsters, the nation's largest trade union.</TEXT><DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co. Chairman Donald Petersenhas announced plans to retire March 31.   The 64-year-old chairman and chief executive shepherded theautomaker from the gloomy financial days of 1980 to huge profitslast year. He announced his plans Friday in an emotional newsconference.   His successor is to be Harold Poling, vice chairman and chiefoperating officer. Poling, 65, will be chairman for three years.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The opening of the Berlin Wall and lifting oftravel restrictions on East German citizens could have immediatebenefits for American companies in West Germany, althoughshort-term prospects for U.S. multinationals to expand into EastGermany are unclear, experts say.   Any move to the East by American and other multinationals won'thappen overnight without a change in the current politicalstructure of the communist nation, but sweeping changes could occurin the next decade, experts said Friday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Soviet Union and the United States willhold high-level discussions this week on a variety of trade topicswith the talks expected to lay the groundwork for increased tradebetween the two countries, U.S. officials say.   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher will head the U.S.delegation to the discussions, which will take place Wednesday andThursday at the Commerce Department. His Soviet counterpart will beKonstantin F. Katushev, Soviet minister of foreign economicrelations.</TEXT><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush promised to ``recapture theAmerican dream of home ownership'' for all Americans and provideshelter for the poor and homeless with a three-year, $4.2 billionspending package.   ``The true measure of success isn't how many families we add tohousing assistance rolls. It's how many families move up and out _and into the ranks of homeowners,'' Bush said Friday.   He did not specify where he would find the money. The dollartotal was specified by aides.</TEXT><DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bicoastal Corp., the former Singer Co. headedby onetime corporate raider Paul Bilzerian, filed for Chapter 11bankruptcy protection following a tumultuous two years of legalbattles and divestments.   A company announcement on Friday said Bicoastal expects to filea reorganization plan soon seeking to ``provide for the payment ofvalid creditors and provide a method to resolve disputed claims.''   Bicoastal said the filing does not affect its remainingsubsidiaries, which include makers of aircraft and nuclear planttraining simulators and weapons control systems.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal bankruptcy judge has granted EasternAirlines an extension of the deadline for filing its disclosurestatement, which is intended to provide details of how it intendsto emerge from Chapter 11 reorganization.   In a hearing Friday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Liflandgave Eastern until Dec. 29 to submit the disclosure statement and arevised reorganization plan.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An investment group including Mary Kay Cosmeticshas amassed a 5 percent stake in Avon Products Inc., it wasdisclosed in an announcement that sparked speculation about arenewed takeover advance on Avon.   Avon earlier this year rebuffed overtures from Mary Kay Corp.Vice Chairman John P. Rochon and rejected outright takeoverproposals from investor Irwin Jacobs and rival direct seller AmwayCorp. The latest disclose was on Friday.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The union representing United Airlines' pilotshas urged its members to support its continued efforts to gaincontrol of parent company, UAL Corp.   The pilots' union also disclosed Friday that since apilot-management bid for the airline failed last month, it has``had conservations'' with Los Angeles billionaire Marvin Davis,who previously bid for UAL, New York investor Saul Steinberg, theinvestment firm Coniston Partners and ``other financial investors.''   The letter did not elaborate on any of the discussions and aspokesman for the pilots' union did not return calls Friday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stock prices closed out an erratic up-and-downweek Friday with a rally that featured a few issues benefiting fromthe political news in Germany. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials climbed 21.92 to 2,625.61.   Bond prices finished little changed.   The dollar rose, especially against the West German mark.   Grain and soybean futures surged; precious metals, copper andenergy futures declined; sugar futures rose and livestock and porkfutures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>